on and government policies; and social and political activism, including feminism and struggles to attain equality with men. Early chapters deal with New France and the first part of the nineteenth century, and the remaining are devoted to the period since 1880, an era in which women’s lives changed rapidly and dramatically.The book concludes that transformation in the means of production, women’s social and political activism (including feminism), and Quebec nationalism are three main keys to understanding the history of Quebec women. Together, the three show that women’s history, far from being an adjunct to “general history,” is essential to a full understanding of the past. Originally published in French with the title Brève histoire des femmes au Québec.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismxHistoryxQuébec (Province)xQuébec. 0aFeminismzQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aFeminismzQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aWomenxHistoryxQuébec (Province). 0aWomenzQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aWomenzQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aWomen's rightsxHistoryxQuébec (Province). 0aWomen's rightszQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aWomen's rightszQuébec (Province)xHistory. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aLanguage Arts & Disciplines: Translation. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aWilson, W. Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458951740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554589517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554589517/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package